# Loadout — Environment Variables

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# DATABASE SETUP
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# LOCAL DEVELOPMENT (SQLite — no external credentials needed)
# Leave DATABASE_URL unset and the app automatically uses an
# ephemeral SQLite file at /tmp/loadout-dev.db.
# To use a persistent local SQLite file instead, set:
# DATABASE_URL="file:./prisma/dev.db"
#
# PRODUCTION (Supabase PostgreSQL)
# Sign up at https://supabase.com, create a project, then find
# your connection strings under:
#   Project Settings → Database → Connection string
#
# IMPORTANT: When using PostgreSQL, also update prisma/schema.prisma
# to use provider = "postgresql" and set both DATABASE_URL and DIRECT_URL.
# The production build uses prisma/schema.postgresql.prisma automatically.
#
# Supabase provides two URLs — use both below:
#   • "Transaction" pooler URL  → DATABASE_URL  (port 6543)
#   • "Session" pooler or direct URL → DIRECT_URL (port 5432)

# Transaction pooler URL (used by the app at runtime via PgBouncer)
# Format: postgresql://postgres.[project-ref]:[password]@aws-0-[region].pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.izqhcelhquqzzujcdlwk:[YOUR-PASSWORD]@aws-1-us-east-2.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1"

# Direct connection URL (used by Prisma migrations only — PostgreSQL only)
# Format: postgresql://postgres.[project-ref]:[password]@aws-0-[region].pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres
DIRECT_URL="postgresql://postgres.izqhcelhquqzzujcdlwk:[YOUR-PASSWORD]@aws-1-us-east-2.pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres"

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SUPABASE CLIENT KEYS (for future Supabase Storage / Auth use)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Found under Project Settings → API
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL="https://izqhcelhquqzzujcdlwk.supabase.co"
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY="your-anon-public-key"

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# JWT_SECRET (required in production)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# A long random string used to sign authentication tokens.
# Generate one with: openssl rand -hex 32
JWT_SECRET="loadout-dev-secret-change-in-production"
